    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-07-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-07-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="434"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d434">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 641.326/5</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">British Embassy</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum</hi>
                </p>
                <p>His Majesty’s Government were approached some weeks ago by the Government of
                    Brazil in regard to the prohibition of the importation of coffee into the United
                    Kingdom.</p>
                <pb facs="0477" n="305" xml:id="pg_305"/>
                <p>His Majesty’s Government had agreed to allow the importation of an amount of
                    Brazilian coffee equivalent to 25 per cent of total imports into the United
                    Kingdom in 1916 from all sources. They are now further considering the
                    importation under license of a small proportion of the normal imports of
                    Brazilian coffee into the United Kingdom if carried on German vessels recently
                    taken over by the Brazilian Government, on condition that these vessels should
                    bring to the United Kingdom other cargo of national importance or else that on
                    their arrival at a British port they should be put at the disposal of the
                    Ministry of Shipping.</p>
                <p>His Majesty’s Ambassador has received instructions to ascertain from the
                    Government of the United States whether they would have any objection to the
                    adoption of this proposal.</p>
                <closer>
                    <dateline rendition="#left">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-07-02">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 2, 1917</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </closer>
            </div>
